KCCAns:
Varieties--Gurguva aloe - Aloe vera (Aloe barbadensis)
           Cape aloe    -           Aloe ferox
           Sagotrin aloe           -Aloe perryi

ALOE INFLORESCENCE--Aloe vera,These are the three mainly cultivated types of aloe. Certain other types like Zanzibar, Uganda, Natal and Hyderabad aloe are having good quality of “aloe gel”. Soil and Climate--Well drained laterite to loamy soils is suited for aloe cultivation. The soil pH must be ranged from 7.0 to 8.5. Commercial cultivation can be done in regions having 25 – 40°C.Seed and sowing---It is propagated through suckers. The suckers are dipped in 0.1 % Carbendazim for five minutes and planted in the field. For planting one hectare of land, 10,000 suckers are required.Planting season---The planting can be done during two seasons namely June – July and September – October.Planting---Field is thoroughly ploughed and beds of suitable sizes are formed. Suckers are planted at 90 x 90 cm spacing.

The remaining amount of urea with standing crops should be given 30-40 days after spraying.

Micronutrient intake comes from using increase in yield. 25 kg. Jink sulfate per hectare should be used once in 3 years. Drip irrigation and fertigation use water soluble fertilizers to increase yield through Sirchai to drip.

III- Active tillering stage: 35-40 DAS
IV- Flowering stage: 50-55 DAS

Crown root initiation and flowering are the most critical stages. Water stagnation should be voided at the time of germination.

recommended for The crop requires 4 - 6 irrigations depending on the soil type and rainfall. Wheat crop requires minimum of 5 irrigations at the following critical stages.
I – Immediately after sowing
II – Crown root intiation : 15-20 DAS 
III- Active tillering stage : 35-40 DAS
IV- Flowering stage : 50-55 DAS
V- Grain filling stage : 70-75 DAS
Crown root initiation and flowering are the most critical stages. Water stagnation should be voided at the time of germination.

Recommended for the crop requires 4 - 6 irrigations depending on the soil type and rainfall. Wheat crop requires minimum of 5 irrigations at the following critical stages.
I – Immediately after sowing
II – Crown root initiation: 15-20 DAS 
III- Active tillering stage: 35-40 DAS
IV- Flowering stage: 50-55 DAS
V- Grain filling stage: 70-75 DAS
Crown root initiation and flowering are the most critical stages. Water stagnation should be voided at the time of germination.

KCCAns:
Before filling the stitch, wet the wall inside the stitches and wet the floor with dough and water solution.

    First layer: - Vegetable substances fill up garbage, stalks, branches, leaves etc. in the entire stitches up to a height of six inches. This 30 cubic feet will contain 100-110 kg of vegetative material. In this layer it would be beneficial to add 3 to 4 percent neem or green leaves of Palash. Which will control the termite.

    Second layer: Mix 4 kg cow dung in 125-150 liters of dung slurry and sprinkle it on the first layer so that the entire vegetative material is well dipped. Keep the amount of water in heat more. If you use biogas slurry, then split 10 lit slurry into 125 to 150 liters of water.

    Third layer: - On the second layer of wet soil, lay cleaned clay 50-60 kg approximately equally. In this order of layers, fill the sutto with a hut of 1.5 feet above its mouth. Typically, the tank will be filled in 11-12 layers. After filling the stitch, apply a layer of 3 inch mud (400 to 500 kg) to sew stitches and leap from cow dung. If the cracks on this, then they should be leaned again.
    Second stuffing: - After 15-20 days, the material filled with stitches will shrink to 8-9 inches, then like the first feeding, fill the vegetative substance, dung slurry and clay soil laying the stitches up to 1.5 feet above their mouth. Seal and seal the same as the first filler.

Seeds & Sowing -

Healthy and large sized tubes (buds) are used for sowing of garlic. Seeds are 5-6 quintals / ha. Direct buds in the middle of Shalakand should not be used for sowing. Sowing pre-buds should be treated with a solution of the combination of MacGebb + Carbendizam 3 gm drug. Garlic is sown in the trash, sprinkler or debugging method. Buds 5-7 cm Should be covered in deep depth and covered with mild soil. At the time of planting, keep the thin part of the buds above. At the time of sowing, the distance of buds from buds is 8 cm. And the distance of the queues is 15 cm. Garlic planter can also be used for crop seeding in large areas.

Fertilizer and fertilizer

The quantity of manure and fertilizer depends on the fertility of the land. Generally, 20-25 tonnes of cow dung or compost per hectare or 5-8 tonnes of Vermicompost, 100 kg / ha. Nutrition, 50 kg Phosphorus and 50 kg Potash is required. 175 kg for this Urea, 109 kg, di ammonium phosphate and 83 kg Mutant of Potash is needed. Dung manure, D.A. The full quantity of P. and potash and half the quantity of urea should be added to the land during the final preparation of the field. The quantity of remaining urea should be given with spraying after 30-40 days in a standing crop.

KCCAns:
Method for Preperation of bordex pest 
1. Dissolve one kilogram of copper sulphate in 5 liter of water in plastic bucket.
2. Dissolve one kilogram of quick lime in 5 liter of water seperately in plastic bucket.
3. Both solution are mixed in one bucket same time.
4. If the prepare mixture is in acidic range, it can be brought to neutral or near alkaline condition by adding some more lime solution into the mixture. 
5. To test the neutrality of the mixture, dip a well polished knife or a sickle in the mixture for few minutes. If reddish deposit appears on the knife/sickle, it indicates the acidic nature of the mixture.

Controlling rubberisation
Avoid excessive application of N to minimise rubberisation. N should not be applied in the form of Urea. Use Ammonium sulphate. Spray 1500 ppm of CCC or MH on 30th day of planting. KCCAns:
Method for Preperation of bordex pest 
1. Dissolve one kilogram of copper sulphate in 5 liter of water in plastic bucket.
2. Dissolve one kilogram of quick lime in 5 liter of water seperately in plastic bucket.
3. Both solution are mixed in one bucket same time.
4. If the prepare mixture is in acidic range, it can be brought to neutral or near alkaline condition by adding some more lime solution into the mixture. 
5. To test the neutrality of the mixture, dip a well polished knife or a sickle in the mixture for few minutes. If reddish deposit appears on the knife/sickle, it indicates the acidic nature of the mixture.

Method for Preperation of bordex pest 
1. Dissolve one kilogram of copper sulphate in 5 liter of water in plastic bucket.
2. Dissolve one kilogram of quick lime in 5 liter of water seperately in plastic bucket.
3. Both solution are mixed in one bucket same time.
4. If the prepare mixture is in acidic range, it can be brought to neutral or near alkaline condition by adding some more lime solution into the mixture. 
5. To test the neutrality of the mixture, dip a well polished knife or a sickle in the mixture for few minutes. If reddish deposit appears on the knife/sickle, it indicates the acidic nature of the mixture.

Method for Preperation of bordex pest 
1. Dissolve one kilogram of copper sulphate in 5 liter of water in plastic bucket.
2. Dissolve one kilogram of quick lime in 5 liter of water seperately in plastic bucket.
3. Both solution are mixed in one bucket same time.
4. If the prepare mixture is in acidic range, it can be brought to neutral or near alkaline condition by adding some more lime solution into the mixture. 
5. To test the neutrality of the mixture, dip a well polished knife or a sickle in the mixture for few minutes. If reddish deposit appears on the knife/sickle, it indicates the acidic nature of the mixture.

Method for Preperation of bordex pest 
1. Dissolve one kilogram of copper sulphate in 5 liter of water in plastic bucket.
2. Dissolve one kilogram of quick lime in 5 liter of water seperately in plastic bucket.
3. Both solution are mixed in one bucket same time.
4. If the prepare mixture is in acidic range, it can be brought to neutral or near alkaline condition by adding some more lime solution into the mixture. 
5. To test the neutrality of the mixture, dip a well polished knife or a sickle in the mixture for few minutes. If reddish deposit appears on the knife/sickle, it indicates the acidic nature of the mixture.

Representative sampling aggregation method-

1- Visit the field in which sampling is to be done by jig-jig and mark it at 10-15 places so that all parts of the farm can be included in it.

2- Remove debris, debris etc. from the upper surface on the selected places.

3- 15 cm at all these places (6-9 inch) dig deeper V shaped cord. Cleansing the pot from the top of the scalp, up to 2 cm from the top. Remove the thick soil from the bottom and put it in a clean bucket or tray.

4- Mix the collected clay well with hand and make a round pile by putting it on clean clothes. Remove the clay from finger to four equal parts and remove the soil separately. Now mix the remaining two parts again and make the rounds. Repeat this procedure until almost half of the remains are left in the soil. This representative will be sample.

5- Keep the dry soil sample in a clean plastic bag and put it in a garment bag. Insert a notice sheet with a sample on which all the information is written, inside a plastic bag and outside a garment bag.

6- Now send these prepared samples to the soil testing laboratory.
